This article is a fact sheet released by the White House Office of the Press Secretary in 2014 about the U.S. government's response to the Ebola virus. The article highlights the government's efforts to enhance domestic preparedness and contain the epidemic in West Africa. Some of the measures taken include implementing new screening measures and travel restrictions, introducing active post-arrival monitoring for passengers from affected countries, tightening protocols for healthcare workers, creating dedicated response teams, and providing training and outreach to relevant stakeholders. The article also mentions the U.S.-led international response to stop Ebola in West Africa, which includes deploying medical and expert personnel, scaling up the presence of the Department of Defense, providing financial support, constructing hospitals and treatment units, and supporting community outreach and safe burials.